decisions.details:
Add dependencies: zig fetch --save <url> (fetches, hashes, adds to build.zig.zon).

Use in build.zig:
  const dep = b.dependency("dep_name", .{ .target = target, .optimize = optimize });
  exe.root_module.addImport("dep_name", dep.module("dep_name"));

Set lazy: true for optional dependencies — access via b.lazyDependency() which returns an optional.

The hash is the source of truth, not the URL. Dependencies are only fetched/built when actually used.

Standard build.zig pattern:
  const target = b.standardTargetOptions(.{});
  const optimize = b.standardOptimizeOption(.{});
  const exe = b.addExecutable(.{ .name = "myapp", .root_module = b.createModule(.{ .root_source_file = b.path("src/main.zig"), .target = target, .optimize = optimize }) });
  b.installArtifact(exe);

Always define: run step, test step, install step.

Advanced patterns: custom build options via b.option(), compile-time options injection via addOptions(), cross-compilation loops over target triples, code generation via addRunArtifact + captureStdOut.

Use b.path() for source files, LazyPath for generated files. Avoid hardcoded paths (breaks caching and composability).
